Is it a pedagogy problem for people like me who need at least 6 months of repeat use to memorize anything? Yes. But also, the nature of learning language, especially ancient ones, is that you’re either suited for the study of it or you aren’t…and I’m not.

To sum up my thoughts, there is the God of Christianity summed up in the epistles and early church writings, and then there’s 19-20th century fundamentalism, one of these things is hurting people. I personally think we need to go back to the beginning to begin undoing the harm.

By the way, read that article for the case example if nothing else.  It is heartbreaking but all too common to see a lack of self worth in religiously traumatized individuals. I’ve even heard of treatment aligning with ACOA (adult children of alcoholics) therapeutic tools.

I will say, this is by no means a call to evangelize to those hurting and tell them “we aren’t all that way” because that helps literally no one. However, for those who wish to find some safety in the church after being traumatized by it? I think we need to do better to help.

Stone also goes on to discuss “spiritual bypassing” in which spirituality and religion are used to bypass “developmental needs, painful feelings, and unresolved wounds.” (326). What if we used religion to address these things, if it is so desired?

I truly think a trauma informed thought process of how we do church, especially in our fellowship, will greatly impact those who were hurt but still desire some sense of spirituality and connection to God.

I want to hop on this train and say holy hell it’s even more disregarded in theological research. If you thought “religious trauma” yielded few results in psychology, it gets real thin in theology; and I think there’s room to do something there.

Religious trauma is more prevalent than the research suggests and often is a contributing factor to many of the problems that bring people to therapy, including depression, anxiety, and relationship difficulties. For this reason, religious trauma deserves careful attention. (324)

In a 2013 article entitled “Thou Shalt Not: Treating Religious Trauma and Spiritual Harm With Combined Therapy” by Alyson M. Stone, the author notes how little psychology talks about the issue of religious trauma.

Dianne D. McDonnell, “Junia, A Woman Apostle,” https://t.co/HHRbjgFXSb (Feb 24, 2018)

*Bernadette Brooten, “Junia . . . Outstanding among the Apostles (Romans 16.7),” in Women Priests: A Catholic Commentary on the Vatican Declarations, ed. Leonard Swidler and Arlene Swidler (New York: Paulist, 1977).

PS: If you desire the list of translations where Junia is named as a woman and which she is not, let me know and I can forward the article where he lists out and details which English translations do what!

There is also the translation issue of "episēmoi en
tois apostolois" (concerning her among the apostles) but this is not the issue at hand. The manuscripts, translations, and tradition support heavily, with evidence, that Junia was a woman named Junia and not a man name Junias.

Preato notes that Brooten doesn't find anyone before Aegidus of Rome (1245-1316) who understands the names to be of "those honorable men". She speculates that it is Aegidus' proximity to Pope Boniface VIII, who desired to limit women's ecclesial power, that led him to this.

Most importantly, to me, is the favor of the Fathers to Junia and her apostleship. Chrysostom even praises her! "Indeed, how great the wisdom of this woman
must have been that she was even deemed worthy of the title of apostle" (PG 60:669f)

"Bible commentators prior to the thirteenth century unanimously favor the female name, Junia. Moving forward, an overwhelming majority of Bible translations from the late 1300s through the mid-1800s translate 'Iounian' as a woman, not as a man." (Preato, 8).
Part of the "issue" is the fact that this name does not appear elsewhere in the Greek NT, however, it was a non-issue for much of Christian history.

Let's use Dennis Preato's article, "Junia, a Female Apostle: An Examination of the Historical Record" (Priscilla Papers. Vol. 33, No. 2, Spring 2019). In this article, he examines the history of Junia as a woman and apostle, especially within English translations.
